    "pubDate": "2025-02-13T12:16:38.000Z",
    "content": "<html><head></head><body><div data-elementor-type=\"wp-post\" data-elementor-id=\"25069\" class=\"elementor elementor-25069\" data-elementor-post-type=\"post\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-845e88c e-flex e-con-boxed e-con e-parent\" data-id=\"845e88c\" data-element_type=\"container\" data-e-type=\"container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t<div class=\"e-con-inner\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-element elementor-element-d82086a elementor-widget elementor-widget-text-editor\" data-id=\"d82086a\" data-element_type=\"widget\" data-e-type=\"widget\" data-widget_type=\"text-editor.default\">\n\t\t\t\t<div class=\"elementor-widget-container\">\n\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t<p><span>With the ERASMUS+ project Watching Videos Like a Historian coming to an end, we invite you to discover how it has equipped educators with the tools to foster students’ media literacy through audiovisual heritage.</span></p><p><span>How can we support students to become critical and thoughtful evaluators of the media they engage with every day? How can we support teachers to develop the tools, skills and confidence to foster media literacy in their lessons? And how can we bring the rich audiovisual heritage in Europe’s museums and archives to classrooms?</span></p><p><span>These are the ques</span></p></div></div></div></div></div></body></html>",
